#Solving electrode-electrolyte system for CO2 to CO reduction

d/dx(-sigma dphi/dx)=0
phi(0)=0 on electrode side (left) 
current density=-sigma dphi/dx=-J0 on electrolyte side (right) 
sigma=0.0002 for x in [0,L/2) (electrode)
sigma=0.0001 for x in [L/2,1] (electrolyte)

At the interface a BV condition is applied
-sigma dphidx (left) \hat{x} = -jco*exp(-k(phi_electrode-phi_electrolyte-E0)) \hat{Electrode->Electrolyte}
= -sigma dphidx (right) \hat{x}

In this case, a cell mask is 
applied in in [0,L/2) and 
IB method is used.

Potential is then solved 
inside the solid (cell mask=0) using
iterative conjugate solves.

Note that the BV current is always directed from 
electrode to electrolyte
